'''Emerge America''' is a non-profit national political organization based in [[San Francisco]] with the mission to increase the number of Democratic women leaders from diverse background in public office through recruitment, training and providing a powerful network.<ref name=":0">{{Cite web|url=https://www.idealist.org/en/nonprofit/dbe10ef52e0d4439b2628f74875a0b5e-emerge-america-san-francisco?|title=Emerge America |website=Idealist|language=en|access-date=2018-01-19}}</ref>
== Background == Andrea Dew Steele is the president and founder.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.cnn.com/2018/01/02/opinions/women-representation-opinion-hunt-steele/index.html|title=A seismic shift in government is coming, and here's who will drive it|last1=Hunt|first1=Swanee |first2=Andrea |last2=Dew|work=CNN |date=2018-04-21|access-date=2018-01-19}}</ref> Steele co-founded the original affiliate, [[Emerge California]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/author/asteele-191|title=Andrea Dew Steele|website=Huffington Post|language=en|access-date=2018-01-19}}</ref> which was formed in 2002. After initial success, Emerge was expanded to a national organization known as Emerge America by Steele in 2005.<ref name=":3">{{Cite news|url=http://www.newhavenindependent.org/index.php/archives/entry/democratic_women_candidates/|title=Female Candidates "Emerge"|date=2017-07-14|work=New Haven Independent|access-date=2018-01-19|language=en-US|first=Betsy |last=Kim}}</ref> Emerge America added affiliates in 6 states in its first year and by the [[National electoral calendar 2016|2016 presidential election]], it had affiliates in 23 states. The organization's strategy is to have affiliates in all 50 states by 2020.<ref name=":0" /><ref name=":2">{{Cite web|url=https://thestoryexchange.org/emerge-america-embracing-50state-strategy/|title=Emerge America is Embracing a 50-State Strategy |website=The Story Exchange|language=en-US|first=Riva |last=Richmond|date=2017-11-09|access-date=2018-01-19}}</ref> Steele says the initial aim is for women to achieve 30% representation for women in government, noting evidence suggests this level passes a [[Critical mass (sociodynamics)|critical mass]] to effectively enact institutional change.<ref name=":2" /> According to Steele, Emerge America has had 3,000 graduates, of which 500 have been elected and are currently serving a political office.<ref name=":3" />
[[Hillary Clinton]] has praised the group as an organization helping to elect [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democrat]]s since the [[2016 US Presidential Election|2016 election]] by using coaching on [[public speaking]], [[fundraising]], networking, and [[government ethics|ethical leadership]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.independent.com/news/2017/may/04/more-women-are-running-office/|title=More Women Are Running — For Office|website=The Independent|language=en|access-date=2017-05-18|first=Starshine |last=Roshell|date=2017-05-04}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.cnn.com/2017/05/15/politics/hillary-clinton-resistance-onward-together/index.html|title=Hillary Clinton officially launches 'resistance' outside group|last=Merica|first=Dan|publisher=CNN|access-date=2017-05-18 ||date=2017-05-16}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.foxnews.com/politics/2017/05/17/clinton-pac-aims-to-boost-left-wing-anti-trump-groups-will-still-have-clout.html|title=Clinton PAC aims to boost left-wing, anti-Trump groups – will she still have clout?|last=Weber|first=Joseph|date=2017-05-17|work=Fox News|access-date=2017-05-18|language=en-US}}</ref> [[A’shanti Gholar]], the Political Director, said enrolment has increased across the board since the 2016 presidential election, and some classes have seen attendance almost double.<ref name=":1">{{Cite news|url=http://www.golocalprov.com/live/live-emerge-americas-gholar-on-surge-of-women-running-for-political-office|title=LIVE: Emerge America’s Gholar on Surge of Women Running For Political Office|date=2018-01-13|work=GoLocalProv|access-date=2018-01-19|language=en}}</ref> Overall, Emerge has seen a 87% increase in the number of applications since the 2016 election.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://womenintheworld.com/2017/11/06/trump-is-propelling-a-record-number-of-women-to-run-for-office/?refresh|title=Trump is propelling a record number of women to run for office|date=2017-11-06|work=Women in the World|access-date=2018-01-19|language=en-US}}</ref> Gholar notes that at the end of 2017, there were 427 women running for a position in the [[United States Congress|U.S. Congress]], compared to 219 women running at the same time in 2015.<ref name=":1" />
