{{Infobox Government agency |agency_name = Joint Advertising Marketing Research & Studies |logo = JAMRS Logo 2014.png |parent_department = [[United States Department of Defense]] |type= Program |headquarters = 4800 Mark Center Drive, Suite 06J25-01 Alexandria, VA 22350-400 |formed= 2002<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nyclu.org/milrec/jamrsinfo |title=Information about the JAMRS Database |publisher= New York Civil Liberties Union |accessdate=11 September 2014}}</ref> |motto = Be heard. Be counted. |chief1_name=Katherine R. Helland |chief1_position=Acting Director |website = {{URL|http://jamrs.defense.gov/}} }}
'''Joint Advertising Marketing Research & Studies''' ('''JAMRS''') is a program run by the [[United States Department of Defense]] to maintain sufficient levels of [[Volunteer military|voluntary service]] in the [[United States Armed Forces]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://jamrs.defense.gov/ |title=JOINT ADVERTISING, MARKET RESEARCH & STUDIES |publisher=U.S. Department of Defense |accessdate=11 September 2014}}</ref> This objective is facilitated by the collection of information about U.S. persons of enlistment age, surveys, and other [[market research]] in a central database made available to military recruiters.
==JAMRS Recruiting Database== JAMRS manages a database (subcontracted by [[Equifax]])<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.motherjones.com/politics/2009/09/few-good-kids |publisher=[[Mother Jones (magazine)|Mother Jones]] |author=David Goodman |title=A Few Good Kids? |date=September–October 2009 |accessdate=11 September 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.projectcensored.org/the-pentagons-child-recruiting-strategy/ |title=The Pentagon's Child Recruiting Strategy |author= Gary Evans |accessdate=11 September 2014}}</ref> of personal information of over 30 million [[United States]] citizens aged 16–25 for the purposes of [[military recruitment]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://jamrs.defense.gov/RecruitingDatabase.aspx |title=JAMRS Recruiting Database |publisher=U.S. Department of Defense |accessdate=11 September 2014}}</ref> Stored information includes, but is not limited to: name, address, email addresses, cell phone numbers, [[ethnicity]], education, and employment information.<ref>[http://vids.myspace.com/index.cfm?fuseaction=vids.individual&videoid=1495382532 Vidéos MySpaceTV : MFZ Mini-Documentary par Military Free Zone<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref><ref>http://www.jamrs.org</ref><ref>http://www.brooklynpeace.org/antimil/jamrs.html</ref><ref>milrec.nyclu.org/2f.html</ref><ref># www.privacycoalition.org/nododdatabase/ letter.html</ref> The database is sourced from public and private organizations such as the [[Selective Service System]], [[Department of Motor Vehicles|Departments of Motor Vehicles]] and [[College Board]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nyclu.org/milrec/jamrs |title=Joint Advertising Market Research Studies (JAMRS) |publisher=New York Civil Liberties Union |accessdate=11 September 2014}}</ref> It is also used by the [[United States Department of Homeland Security|Department of Homeland Security]] and other federal agencies for research purposes and for the Military Draft.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://jamrs.defense.gov/MarketResearchStudies.aspx |title=Market Research |publisher=U.S. Department of Defense |accessdate=11 September 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://jamrs.defense.gov/Affiliations.aspx |title=Affiliations |publisher=U.S. Department of Defense |accessdate=11 September 2014}}</ref> The names and contact information of all registrants in the [[Selective Service System]] are distributed to JAMRS on a quarterly basis."<ref>[http://www.jamrs.org/aff.php JAMRS Affiliations]</ref>
===Opt-out=== Individuals whose information is present in the JAMRS database can opt out of having that information shared with recruiters,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nyclu.org/files/optoutletter_02012010.doc |title=Opt-out form}}</ref> but it cannot be permanently removed.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nyclu.org/milrec/jamrs |title=Joint Advertising Market Research Studies (JAMRS) |publisher=New York Civil Liberties Union |accessdate=11 September 2014}}</ref>
==Legal challenges== The [[New York Civil Liberties Union]] filed a lawsuit against the Department of Defense in 2006 (Hanson v. Rumsfeld) claiming the unconstitutionality of the JAMRS database. They succeeded in getting a settlement forcing the DOD to stop collecting Social Security Numbers, keep student information for only three years, restrict the ages of students included in the database, and maintain better privacy standards for student information. Also, the Department of the Defense clarified the procedure for opting out of the database. The Department of Defense updated those procedures in January 2011.<ref>http://www.nyclu.org/milrec/jamrs</ref><ref>http://www.nyclu.org/files/hanson_v_rumsfeld_complaint_042406.pdf</ref>
==Futures Survey== This survey was distributed by [[United States Postal Service|postal mail]] to a randomly selected group of 16- to 24-year-olds. Information requested included education, career plans, and attitudes toward the military.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://jamrs.defense.gov/MarketResearchStudies/FuturesStudy.aspx |title=Futures Study |publisher=U.S. Department of Defense |accessdate=11 September 2014}}</ref> $2.00 was included with the survey and participants were promised an additional $10.00 upon completion.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.dailyranger.com/story.php?story_id=12590 |publisher=Daily Ranger |title=Think carefully before filling out military survey for young people |author=Misti Bolte |date= 8 May 2014 |accessdate=11 September 2014}}</ref>
