{{primary sources|date=May 2008}} [[Image:Tricontinentalmagazine.PNG|right|thumb|Logo of the magazine]] '''''Tricontinental''''' is a [[Left-wing politics|leftist]] [[quarterly]] [[magazine]] founded during the [[Tricontinental Conference]]. The magazine is the official publication of the [[Cuba]]n organisation [[OSPAAAL]] which also publishes it.<ref name=milt>{{cite journal|author1=Brian Williams|title=‘Tricontinental’ magazine marks 150th anniversary of José Martí|journal=The Militant|date=28 April 2003|volume=67|issue=14|url=http://www.themilitant.com/2003/6714/671466.html|accessdate=24 December 2015}}</ref><ref name=abeb/> It has its headquarters in [[Havana]].<ref name=abeb/>
The magazine receives much funding from sympathetic European groups.{{Citation needed|date=November 2017}}
From the founding of ''Tricontinental'' in August 1967<ref name=abeb>{{cite web|title=The Tricontinental Solidarity Poster. / El Cartel De Solidaridad Tricontinental|url=http://www.abebooks.com/Tricontinental-Solidarity-Poster-Cartel-Solidaridad-OSPAAAL/1089294261/bd|publisher=AbeBooks|accessdate=24 December 2015}}</ref> until the [[dissolution of the Soviet Union]], which led to a rapid recession in the [[Economy of Cuba|Cuban economy]], propaganda posters were folded up and placed inside copies of the magazine, however, this was stopped, along with publication of ''Tricontinental'', due to [[ink]] shortages and [[finance|financial]] trouble.
''Tricontinental'' began to be printed again in 1995. In 2000, the decision was made to begin to reprint posters.
The magazine is distributed around the world, and at its height, 87 [[country|countries]] received ''Tricontinental'', and there were more than 100,000 [[subscription|subscribers]], mostly [[student]]s. At one time, it was very common for posters from issues of ''Tricontinental'' to be posted on the walls of student [[community]] centres.
