{{Orphan|date=June 2018}}
'''Zuurakan Kaynazarova''' ({{lang-ky|'''Зууракан Кайназарова'''}}) (June 18, 1902 – June 4, 1982) was a [[Kyrgyzstan]]i [[collective farm]] worker and politician during the [[Soviet Union|Soviet]] era.
Kaynazarova was born in the village of Dzhalamysh in the [[Sokuluk District]] of [[Chuy Region]] in northern Kyrgyzstan. Her career as a farmworker began in 1929, and by the 1930s she was managing record numbers of [[beet]]s in her harvests; in one year, 1947, she managed to harvest {{convert|15|ha}} worth of beets. As a result, she was designated team leader for several beet farms in the Chuy Region. During [[World War II]] she worked to produce crops to aid the war effort, and took in a number of war orphans. Her abilities led Kaynazarova to receive a number of honors during her career. She received the [[Order of Lenin]] three times, in 1941, 1947, and 1948; in 1946 she was awarded the [[Order of the Red Banner of Labour]], and in 1948 and 1957 she was named a [[Hero of Socialist Labour]]. As a member of the [[Communist Party of the Soviet Union]] she was a deputy to the [[Supreme Soviet of the USSR]]; she also serve as a member and vice-chairman of the [[Supreme Council (Kyrgyzstan)|Supreme Soviet of the Kirghiz SSR]].<ref name="centralasien.org">{{cite web|url=https://centralasien.org/en/40-women-of-kyrgyzstan-portraits/zuurakan-kaynazarova/|title=Zuurakan Kaynazarova|date=24 January 2017|publisher=centralasien.org|accessdate=28 November 2017}}</ref> Kaynazarova retired in 1958 and died in 1982; in retirement she lived in Frunze, today [[Bishkek]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.warheroes.ru/hero/hero.asp?Hero_id=18647|title=Кайназарова Суракан|website=www.warheroes.ru|accessdate=28 November 2017}}</ref> She continues to be memorialized in her native country.<ref name="centralasien.org"/> A bust of her in pink [[granite]] was erected in Bishkek in 1975, along Dzherzhinsky (today Erkindik) boulevard.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kyrgyzstantravel.info/kyrgyzstan/bishkek/monuments/monuments.htm|title=Monuments in Bishkek. Путешествие по Кыргызстану. Туризм и приключения.|first=Путешествие по|last=Кыргызстану|website=www.kyrgyzstantravel.info|accessdate=28 November 2017}}</ref> A high school in her home region bears her name, and she has been the subject of a documentary film; furthermore her birthday has been designated the day on which the work of rural women is recognized and honored.<ref name="centralasien.org"/>
